data.content:
## What breaks

In .NET 11, EF Core's Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

## How to fix

Convert all sync calls to their async counterparts:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory; no I/O occurs.
- All query materializers (`ToList`, `First`, `Single`, `Count`, `Any`, etc.) must use their `*Async` variants.
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- The old opt-in (`EnableSyncOverAsync = true` / `CosmosOptionsExtension`) is no longer recognized and will itself throw on startup.

Callers up the stack will also need to become `async`/`await` — this change propagates through your controllers/services.
